{{Arab culture}}
'''Arab folk dances''' ({{lang-ar|رقص عربي|raqs ʿarabiyy}}) also referred to as ''Oriental dance'', ''[[Middle-Eastern dance]] and'' ''Eastern dance'', are the traditional folk dances of the [[Arabs]] in [[Arab world]]. Arab dance has many different styles, including the three main types of folklore, classical, and contemporary. It is enjoyed and implemented throughout the Arab region, from [[North Africa]] to the [[Middle East]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/148667773|title=Popular culture in the Arab world : arts, politics, and the media|last=1970-|first=Hammond, Andrew,|date=2007|publisher=American University in Cairo Press|isbn=9774160541|location=Cairo, Egypt|oclc=148667773}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=DMGpDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA11&dq=arab+dance&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiqw4nzuuXWAhUQa1AKHWZeBRYQ6AEIMTAC#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of World Folk Dance|last=Snodgrass|first=Mary Ellen|date=2016-08-08|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781442257498|language=en}}</ref>

The term "Arabic dance" is often associated with the belly dance.<ref>{{Cite book|url=|title=Feminist Theory and Pop Culture|last=Trier-Bieniek|first=Adrienne|date=2015|publisher=Springer|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=4|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=A Symphony of Flavors: Food and Music in Concert|last=Murray|first=Edmundo|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|year=|location=|pages=34|language=en}}</ref> However, there are many styles of traditional Arab dance,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Traditional Arabic Dance|url=https://ourpastimes.com/the-traditional-arabic-dance-12347223.html|website=Our Pastimes|language=en}}</ref> and many of them have a long history.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=k-LzWEYkzt8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=|title=Dancing Arabs|last=Kashua|first=Sayed|date=2007-12-01|publisher=Grove/Atlantic, Inc.|isbn=9781555846619|language=en}}</ref> These may be folk dances, or dances that were once performed as rituals or as entertainment spectacle, and some may have been performed in the imperial court.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=FpRhAAAAIAAJ&q=|title=The Art of Music: The dance|last=Mason|first=Daniel Gregory|date=1916|publisher=National Society of Music|language=en}}</ref> Coalescence of oral storytelling, poetry recital, and performative music and dance as long-standing traditions in [[Arab history]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=x-1fOcxHJ8oC&pg=PA179&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Arab National Project in Youssef Chahine's Cinema|last=Khouri|first=Malek|date=2010|publisher=American Univ in Cairo Press|isbn=9789774163548|language=en}}</ref>&nbsp;Among the best-known of the Arab traditional dances are the [[Belly dance]] and the [[Dabke]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/320803968|title=Serpent of the Nile : women and dance in the Arab world|last=1950-|first=Buonaventura, Wendy,|date=2010|publisher=Interlink Books|isbn=1566567912|edition=Updated and rev.|location=Northampton, Mass.|oclc=320803968}}</ref>

Traditional dancing is still popular among [[Arab diaspora|expatriate Arabs]], and has also been very successfully `exported' to international folk dance groups, [[circle dance]] groups and expressive dance all over the world. All dancers wear the traditional costume to embody the history of their culture and tell their ancestors stories.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=6ZIQAQAAQBAJ&dq=arab+dance&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=Arab-American Faces and Voices: The Origins of an Immigrant Community|last=Boosahda|first=Elizabeth|date=2010-01-01|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=9780292783133|language=en}}</ref>

== History ==
[[Image:الفلكلور الشعبى فى مصر 28 (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|upright|A dancer dancing Raqs Baladi in Cairo]]
Historically, dance has always been an important part of [[Arab culture]]. One of the oldest social dances enjoyed by the [[Arab people]] in the Middle East and North Africa of all ages and sexes at ceremonial events named Raqs Baladi means in ({{lang-ar|بلدي|translit=baladī|translit-std=ALA|link=no}}<span style="margin-left:3px">;</span> [[Arabic nouns and adjectives#Nisba|relative]]-adjective "of town", "local", "rural", comparable to English "[[:wikt:folk#Adjective|folk]]", with a lower-class connotation). During the series of invasions on the Arab world, Europeans were influenced by Arab culture, During the [[French campaign in Egypt and Syria]] in 1798, Europeans were interested in the Arab world. In the middle of the 19th century, the Arab lands, especially the [[Levant]], [[Mesopotamia]] and [[Egypt]] were collectively referred to as the East. The Middle East attracted European painters and writers in the 19th century who came to be orientalists, among the most prominent personalities are [[Jean-Léon Gérôme]], [[Eugène Delacroix]] and [[Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Buonaventura|first1=Wendy|title=Serpent of the Nile : women and dance in the Arab world|date=2010|publisher=Saqi|location=London|isbn=0863566286|edition=[Newly updated ed.]}}</ref> 

The Oriental motion has undoubtedly contributed to the misconception of the popular dance as a dance of temptation, conducted for the pleasure of men. In fact, because of the traditional gender segregation, women in the Middle East usually dance only in the women's company between parents and friends. Sometimes a professional dancer and musicians were invited to the women's Caucus. Today, gender segregation is not strictly practised in many urban areas, and sometimes both men and women dance socially at family and/or community events.

Arabic dance was performed in the United States in 1893 at the [[World's Columbian Exposition]], which included an exhibition entitled "The streets of Cairo". The exhibition was attended by dancers from several [[Arab countries]] from the Middle East and North Africa, including [[Syria]] and [[Algeria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/11/arts/design/a-wriggle-in-time-historical-artifacts-of-belly-dancing.html|title=A Wriggle in Time: Historical Artifacts of Belly Dancing|last=Kahn|first=Eve M.|date=2016-11-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The term "belly dancing" is often credited to [[Sol Bloom]], its entertainment director, but referred to the dance as ''danse du ventre'', the name used by the French in Algeria. In his memoirs, Bloom states, "when the public learned that the literal translation was "belly dance", they delightedly concluded that it must be salacious and immoral...I had a gold mine."<ref>Donna Carlton (1995) ''Looking for Little Egypt''. Bloomington, Indiana: International Dance Discovery Books. {{ISBN|0-9623998-1-7}}.</ref>

== Types of dance ==
Arabs have their own [[Arabic music|music]] and dance which take part of their [[Arab identity|identity]]. There are a lot of Arab traditional dances styles as the [[Arab world]] is a vast area. Men are also as involved as [[Women in Arab societies|women]]. Here are four kinds of traditional dances in the Arab world.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://www.firdaous.org/traditional-dances-arab-world.htm|title=Traditional dances of the Arab world - Firdaous|date=2017-06-02|work=Firdaous|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref>

===  Arab classic dances ===
Those dances dated from the antiquity and have not ceased to evolve in history and in time.<ref name=":2" />

==== Belly dance ====
{{main article|Belly dance}}
[[Image:ABellydancerWithTraditionalEgyptianSaidiOutfit.jpg|thumb|An Arab bellydancer]]
''Belly dance'' also referred to as ''Arabic dance'' ({{lang-ar|رقص شرقي|Raqs sharqi}} is an Arab expressive dance,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Snodgrass|first1=Mary Ellen|title=The Encyclopedia of World Folk Dance|date=2016|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781442257498|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=DMGpDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA11&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=editor|first1=Justine J. Reel, PHD, LPC, CC-AASP,|title=Eating disorders : an encyclopedia of causes, treatment, and prevention|date=2013|publisher=Greenwood|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=1440800588}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Buonaventura|first1=Wendy|title=Serpent of the Nile : women and dance in the Arab world|date=2010|publisher=Saqi|location=London|isbn=0863566286|edition=[Newly updated ed.]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hammond|first1=Andrew|title=Popular culture in the Arab world : arts, politics, and the media|date=2007|publisher=American University in Cairo Press|location=Cairo, Egypt|isbn=9774160541|edition=1. publ.}}</ref> which emphasizes complex movements of the torso.<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Deagon|first=Andrea|title=In Search of the Origins of Dance|date=1984|degree=PhD|publisher=[[University of North Carolina Wilmington]]|url=http://people.uncw.edu/deagona/raqs/origins.htm|doi=}}</ref> Many boys and girls in countries where belly dancing is popular will learn how to do it when they are young. The dance involves movement of many different parts of the body; usually in a [[circle|circular]] way.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BellyDancer|title=Belly Dancer - TV Tropes|website=tvtropes.org|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> Both women and men can belly dance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bellydancers.wikidot.com/|title=Belly Dancing Information - Belly Dancing|website=bellydancers.wikidot.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-23}}</ref>

==== Shamadan ====
[[File:SHAMADAN.jpg|thumb|Dance of Shamadan]]
''Shamadan'' ({{lang-ar|شمعدان}}) is a large candelabrum balanced on top of a dancer's head, in a tradition unique to [[Egypt]]ian dance.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sakkara.de/en/217/|title=Shamadan - Sakkara|website=www.sakkara.de|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sakti-international.com/candelabra.html|title=SAKTI RINEK - World-Famous Bellydancer|last=|first=|date=|website=www.sakti-international.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://al-bab.com/music-section/arab-music-dance|title=Arab music: dance|work=al-bab.com|access-date=2017-10-07|language=en}}</ref> This dance prop is historically used in the Egyptian wedding procession, or [[Zaffa|zeffah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gildedserpent.com/art43/gamilaniledance3candl.htm|title=Gamila and Lucy tell about the Shamadan or Candelabra for the Gilded Serpent|website=www.gildedserpent.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> The wedding procession traditionally occurs at night, winding its way through the streets of the neighborhood from the home of the bride's parents to her new home at the groom's house. This is the official moving of the bride and is led by a dancer, musicians and singers, followed by the wedding party and their friends and family.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=J1ZS2dhWDMQC&pg=PA150&lpg=PA150&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Culture and Customs of Egypt|last=Asante|first=Molefi K.|date=2002|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=9780313317408|language=en}}</ref>

==== Raqs Sharqi ====
{{main article|Raqs Sharqi}}
[[File:20111110 Egypt 0421 Cairo dinner cruise.jpg|thumb|Raqs Sharqi in Cairo]]
''Raqs Sharqi'' ({{lang-ar|رقص شرقي}}) is the classical Egyptian style of [[belly dance]] that developed during the first half of the 20th century. This dance is [[Pre-Islamic Arabia|pre-Islamic]] and is an oral tradition which has changed over the centuries. Some people believe that it originated as a fertility or Goddess worshipping dance, and in [[North Africa]] it can still be used to help during childbirth.<ref>{{cite web|last1=taylor|first1=carolyne|title=Raqs Sharqi|url=http://www.spiritdancer.co.uk/raqs.htm|website=www.spiritdancer.co.uk}}</ref>

==== Baladi ====
{{main article|Baladi}}
[[File:الفلكلور الشعبى فى مصر 23.jpg|thumb|Dance of Baladi in Egypt]]
''Baladi'' ({{lang-ar|بلدي}}) means “of the country” and is a style of Egyptian folk dance from the early 20th century which is still very popular. Thus, ‘Egyptian Beledi’ means ‘of the country of Egypt’<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlantabellydance.com/Overview/EgyptianFolkloric.html|title=Overview of Belly Dance: Egyptian Folkloric style belly dancing|website=www.atlantabellydance.com|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> It came about when farmers moved to the city and began dancing in small spaces. Egyptians have Baladi people, Baladi bread, Baladi rhythms, Baladi music and Baladi dance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bellydanceu.net/styles/bellydance-styles-egyptian-baladi/|title=Learn Bellydance Styles: Egyptian Baladi - Bellydance U|date=2015-08-01|work=Bellydance U|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shira.net/baladi.htm|title="Baladi" by Hossam Ramzy|last=Elliot|first=Shira Julie|date=|website=www.shira.net|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref> It is a folk/social form of bellydance. It is more stationary than [[Raqs Sharqi|raqs sharqi]], with little use of the arms, and the focus is on hip movements. Baladi dance has a 'heavy' feeling, with the dancer appearing relaxed and strongly connected to the ground. It is performed to baladi or folk music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shemsdance.com/articles/egyptian-baladi-and-the-baladi-taksim/|title=Egyptian Baladi and the Baladi Taksim|website=www.shemsdance.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>

==== Almeh ====
{{main article|Almeh}}
''Almeh'' ({{lang-ar|عالمة|translit=ʕálma}} {{IPA-ar|ˈʕælmæ|IPA}}; the peasant pronunciation is ''{{transl|arz|ʕálme}}'' or ''{{transl|arz|ʕālme}}'', plural {{lang|arz|عوالم}} ''{{transl|arz|ʕawālim}}'' {{IPA-arz|ʕæˈwæːlem, -lɪm|}}, from Arabic: ''{{transl|ar|Wehr|ʻālima}}'', from {{lang|ar|[[:wikt:علم|علم]]}}  "to know, be learned")
was the name of a class of [[courtesan]]s or female entertainers in [[History of Muslim Egypt|Egypt]], women educated to sing and recite classical poetry and to discourse wittily.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.shira.net/art/gerome-almeh.htm|title=Dance of the Almeh, by Jean-Léon Gerôme|last=Gerôme|first=Jean-Léon|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>

==== Ouled Nail ====
{{main article|Ouled Nail}}
[[File:DANSEUSE OULED NAIL2.jpg|thumb|Dancer of Ouled Nail]]
''[[Ouled Nail]]'' ({{lang-ar|أولاد نايل}}) originated a style of music, sometimes known as [[Bou Saâda]] music after the town near their homeland. In [[belly dancing]], the term refers to a style of dance originated by the Ouled Naïl, noted for their way of dancing. Which involves small, rapid foot movements paired with vigorous torso and hip movements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belly-dance.org/ouled-nail.html |title=Ouled Nail |publisher=Belly-dance.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jasminjahal.com/articles/99_06.html |title="The Ouled Nail of Algeria", by Jasmin Jahal, June 1999 |publisher=Jasminjahal.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-28}}</ref>

==== Ghawazi ====
{{main article|Ghawazi}}
'' Ghawazi'' ({{lang-ar|غوازي}}) (also ''ghawazee'') [[dance]]rs of [[Egypt]] were a group of female traveling dancers. The Ghawazee perform, unveiled, in the public streets, even to amuse the rabble. Their dancing has little of elegance; its chief peculiarity being a very rapid vibrating motion of the hips, from side to side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gildedserpent.com/articles25/edwinakhairiyyastruggles.htm|title=Edwina Nearing for the Gilded Serpent|website=www.gildedserpent.com|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>

===  Folk dances ===
Those dances are performed during the civil celebrations or events as birth, death, wedding or a social ascent and sometimes during religious festivals.<ref name=":2" />

==== Dabke ==== 
{{main article|Dabke}}
[[File:Palestinian girls dancing Dabke.jpg|thumb|Palestinian girls dancing traditional Dabke]] 
''Dabke'' ({{lang-ar|دبكة}}), is an Arab folk dance event forming part of the shared [[Sociocultural system|sociocultural]] [[landscape]] of the [[Levant]].<ref>
*{{cite web|title=The Dabke-An Arabic Folk Dance|url=https://dancehistorydevelopment.wordpress.com/2013/05/09/the-dabke-an-arabic-folk-dance/|website=History and Development of Dance/ Brockport|date=9 May 2013}}
*{{cite book|last1=Veal|first1=Michael E.|last2=Kim|first2=E. Tammy|title=Punk Ethnography: Artists & Scholars Listen to Sublime Frequencies|date=2016|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|isbn=9780819576545|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=Oqv3DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA289&dq=|language=en}}
*{{cite book|last1=Kabir|first1=Nahid|title=Young American Muslims: Dynamics of Identity|date=2012|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=9780748669967|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=1bZvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA85&dq=|language=en}}
*{{cite web|title=Event: Dabke Dance Workshop – Vassar BDS|url=http://vsa.vassar.edu/orgs/vassarsjp/2016/01/21/event-dabke-dance-workshop/|website=vsa.vassar.edu}}
*{{cite book|last1=York|first1=Museum of the City of New|title=A Community of Many Worlds: Arab Americans in New York City|date=2002|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=9780815607397|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=qFSIf5Zz26gC&pg=PA258&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|language=en}}
*{{cite book|last1=Stanton|first1=Andrea L.|title=Cultural Sociology of the Middle East, Asia, and Africa: An Encyclopedia|date=2012|publisher=SAGE|isbn=9781412981767|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=GtCL2OYsH6wC&pg=PA316&dq=|language=en}}
*{{cite book|last1=Cavendish|first1=Marshall|last2=Corporation|first2=Marshall Cavendish|title=Peoples of Western Asia|date=2006|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=9780761476771|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=gDLdfF7DyL0C&pg=PA282&dq=|language=en}}
*{{cite book|last1=Don|last2=Hunt|first2=Mary|title=Hunts' guide to southeast Michigan|date=1990|publisher=Midwestern Guides|location=Waterloo, Mich.|isbn=0962349909}}
*{{cite web|title=Dabke|url=http://www.cpamonline.com/dabke.html|website=Canadian Palestinian Association in Manitoba}} It is performed in [[Lebanon]], [[Jordan]], [[Iraq]], [[Syria]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], [[Hatay Province|Hatay]] and [[Saudi Arabia|Northern Saudi Arabia]].</ref> Twice, Dabke was made into a fixed canon of movement patterns and steps which, through repeated ececution, served to consolidate [[Norm (social)|behavioral norms]] and [[Culture|cultural]]. Legend says that people in that region during that era made the roofs of their houses with tree [[branch]]es and mud.

Anytime the weather would change, the mud would crack and members of their family or community would come and help patch it by forming a line and joining hands and stomping the mud into place. In colder months, they would sing to help keep their bodies warm.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ch/books?id=OfRAsefaeVEC&pg=PA36&dq=|title=Dance and Authenticity in Israel and Palestine: Performing the Nation|last=Kaschl|first=Elke|date=2003-01-01|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004132384|language=en}}</ref>

==== Deheyeh ====
''Deheyeh'' ({{lang-ar|الدحية}}), Is a [[Bedouin]] dance practiced in [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], [[Jordan]], [[Saudi Arabia|northern Saudi Arabia]], some of the [[Arab states of the Persian Gulf|Gulf states]], the [[Syrian Desert|Syrian desert]] and [[Iraq]]. It was practiced before the wars to stir up enthusiasm among the members of the tribe, and at the end of the battles in ancient times describe the battle and the tournaments, but now it is practiced on occasions such as [[Arab wedding|weddings]], [[holiday]]s and other [[Party|celebrations]].

===  Popular dances ===
Popular dances involve all forms artistic expressions of a people.<ref name=":2" />

==== Khaleegy ====
{{main article|Khaleegy (dance)}}
[[File:Arab girls dancing Khaleegy dance.jpg|thumb|Arab girls dancing Khaleegy dance]]
''Khaleegy'' ({{lang-ar|خليجي}}) is an dance performed in the countries of the [[Arabian Peninsula]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bellydanceu.net/styles/learn-bellydance-styles-khaleegy/|title=Learn Belly Dance Styles: Khaleegy - Bellydance U|date=2015-08-05|work=Bellydance U|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref> A long "[[Thawb]]" is worn which the dancer holds up in front.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sakkara.de/en/345/|title=Khaleegy - Sakkara|website=www.sakkara.de|language=en|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref> There is a step with it, but the main feature is the hair tossing as the head swings from side to side. The name of the dance literally means “[[Arab states of the Persian Gulf|gulf]]” in Arabic and it is danced by local women in weddings and other social events. Khaleegy is a joyful, lively, expressive, gestural and delicate dance performed in events involving happiness and celebration (like weddings).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellydancegeek.com/2013/03/the-big-5-khaleegy/|title=The Big 5: Khaleegy - Belly Dance Geek|date=2013-03-12|work=Belly Dance Geek|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://stepfeed.com/7-khaleeji-songs-you-ll-never-get-enough-of-8843|title=7 Khaleeji songs you'll never get enough of|date=2016-09-21|work=StepFeed|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref> Women dance in complicity and it is often started with one of them standing alone in the dance floor to begin the dance, and then the others join her.The main body parts involved in the dance are the hands, the head and the "Thawb" itself. The hair, apart from the "Thawb" is the main element used to dance [[Khaleegy (dance)|Khaleegy]]: women let their long hair “dance” moving it from side to side, back and forth, in circle and making other figures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shemsdance.com/articles/khaliji-thobe-nashal-dance-arabian-gulf/|title=Khaliji Raqs Na’ashat Dance & Iraqi Kawliya|website=www.shemsdance.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref> Recently it has become very popular among belly dancers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mellilah.com/blog/khaliji-dance/|title=Khaliji Dance History {{!}} Everything Belly Dance Blog|date=2008-10-14|work=Everything Belly Dance|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref>

The Khaleegy dance is most commonly performed to a hypnotic 2/4 rhythm with two heavy beats and a pause, called the saudi, khaliji, or adany rhythm (from [[Yemen]]). It should be noted that there is not one khaliji rhythm but hundreds, as this dance represents many countries of the Gulf area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chronicle.fanack.com/bahrain/society-media-culture/culture/khaliji-dance/|title=Khaliji dance|work=Fanack Chronicle|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref>

==== Ardah ==== 
{{main article|Ardah}}
[[File:Donald Trump with ceremonial swordsmen on his arrival to Murabba Palace, May 2017.jpg|thumb|[[Salman of Saudi Arabia|Salman]] and [[Donald Trump]] dance the Najdi ardah.]]
''Ardah'' ({{lang-ar|العرضة|translit=al-‘arḍah|translit-std=ALA-LC}}) is a type of [[folkloric]] [[dance]] in [[Arabia]]. The dance is performed with two rows of men opposite of one another, each of whom may or may not be wielding a sword or cane, and is accompanied by drums and spoken poetry.<ref name="urkevich1"/>  In the Emirates, the local version is called the Iyala.

The term 'Ardah' is thought to derive from the [[Arabic]] verb ''ard'' meaning 'to show' or 'to parade'. It was so named because its purpose was to publicly display the fighting strength of a tribe and boost morale before an armed engagement.<ref name="urkevich1">{{cite book|last=Urkevich|first=Lisa|title=Music and Traditions of the Arabian Peninsula: Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain, and Qatar|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gy-cBQAAQBAJ|format=Google Play|page=131/689|chapter=5|publisher=Routledge|date=19 December 2014|isbn=978-0415888721}}</ref> Although there are regional variations of the particular rendition of ardah, the purpose it serves is nearly identical throughout the Arabian Peninsula.<ref name="urkevich1"/>

==== Hagallah ====  
[[File:Hagallah dancing.jpg|thumb|Hagallah dancing]]
''hagallah'' ({{lang-ar|هجاله}}) is a folkloric dance of celebration known as the ''hagallah'' is performed by the settled ''[[Bedouin]] ''(bedu) of Mersa Matruh in Western [[Egypt]] and is often performed during the date harvest, which is the wedding season in that area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.home.aone.net.au/~aziza/Hagallah.html|title=Egypt2|website=www.home.aone.net.au|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>  Hagallah is also known in areas of neighbouring Libya and is related to ''kaf'' (clapping) dances in other regions of the Middle East., hagallah is performed by the bedouin of western Egypt. It has been described as a wedding dance and also as a girl's coming-of-age dance.<ref name=":1" />

==== Schikhatt  ====
''Schikhatt'' ({{lang-ar|شيخات}}) in Classical Arabic, the word&nbsp;''sheikha''&nbsp;is the feminine of&nbsp;''sheikh'': a person with knowledge, experience, wisdom. In Maghrebi (Moroccan Arabic), "sheikha" limits its meaning to specify a woman with carnal knowledge extensive enough to teach others. Is an erotic women-only dance, originally performed for the bride before her wedding, with the idea of teaching her how she would be expected to move in the marriage bed.<ref name=":0" />

==== Guedra ==== 
''Guedra'' ({{lang-ar|كدرة}}) is a dancer from the desert region of Morocco's south west, performed to induce an altered state of consciousness, with a solo performer beginning the dance with hand movements, then swinging the head and torso until a trance state is reached.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/2516742|title=Moroccan Dance, Guedra & Schikhat|website=www.brownpapertickets.com|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> Guedra dancers are single or divorced women. Sometimes men from the audience will enquire with a view to marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.casbahdance.org/the-guedra-morocco-brings-it-to-denver/|title=The Guedra: Morocco Brings It to Denver {{!}} Morocco & the Casbah Dance Experience|website=www.casbahdance.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>

==== Yowla ====
{{main article|Yowla}}
''Yowla '' ({{lang-ar|اليولة}}) is traditional dance in the  [[United Arab Emirates]]. It involves spinning and throwing a rifle dummy made entirely of wood and metal plating.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-yowla-dance|title=Largest yowla dance|work=Guinness World Records|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-GB}}</ref>

=== Sacred dances ===
[[File:Dance in Religious concert.jpg|thumb|Mwald celebrations of the Prophet's family in Egypt is the best tables stretched out and hints from the days of eternity, and celebrates the people of God in Egypt Bmwald the Prophet's family at an annual fixed dates]]
Those sacred dances are related to the dominant religion of the Arab world which is the Islam. They are particularly linked to sufism which is the heart of the islamic tradition inaugurated by the Prophet.<ref name=":2" />

==== Tanoura ====
{{main article|Tanoura (dance)}}
''Tanoura'' ({{lang-ar|التنورة}}) Is an [[Egypt|Egyptian]] folk dance with obvious [[Sufism|Sufi]] origins,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://egypt-d.com/?p=7104|title=The Egyptian Folklore Dance ” Tanoura Dance”|work=وصف مصر - wasf masr|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en-US}}</ref> which today became an important ritual of the celebration rituals performed on many occasions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.memphistours.com/Dubai/Emirates-Travel-Guide/dubai-things-to-do/wiki/tanoura-dance-dubai-desert|title=Tanoura Dance {{!}} Dubai Tanoura Show|website=www.memphistours.com|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref> The dance is a rhythmic dance performed collectively by circular movements, which stems from the mystical Islamic sense of philosophical basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.egyptiancastle.com/cafe/belly/tanoura/tanoura01.htm|title=The Egyptian Castle - El Tanoura|website=www.egyptiancastle.com|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref> It sees that the movement in the universe starts from a point and ends at the same point and therefore reflects this concept in their dance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lonelyplanet.com/thorntree/forums/africa/egypt/tanoura-dance|title=Tanoura Dance|last=Planet|first=Lonely|website=www.lonelyplanet.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref> Their movements come as if they are drawing halos, drenched in space. The word ''tanoura'' or ''tannoura'' refers to the colorful skirt worn by the whirler, with a color representing each [[Sufi order]].<ref name="feedfury">{{Cite web|url=http://entertainment.feedfury.com/content/34279531-egyptian-folk-dance-tanoura.html|title=Egyptian folk dance : Tanoura|website=entertainment.feedfury.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-27}}</ref>

==== Zar ====
{{main article|Zār}}
''Zār'' ({{lang-ar|زار}}) is a dance performed to drive away evil spirits. It originated in the Sudan but is also popular among women in Egypt.<ref name=":1" />

